{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"90f0cf09-c339-4e22-a3e7-df8f9e5ff9e2","content":"`SafeAreaEdges` alone doesn't make content draw behind system bars — it only controls how safe-area insets are applied to your layout. You likely need two additional things:\n\n**1. Hide Shell/Navigation chrome:**\n```xml\nShell.NavBarIsVisible=\"False\"\nShell.TabBarIsVisible=\"False\"\nNavigationPage.HasNavigationBar=\"False\"\n```\n\n**2. Platform-specific edge-to-edge configuration:**\n\n**iOS** — tell the page not to respect safe area:\n```xml\nxmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"\nios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\"\n```\n\n**Android** — draw behind system bars (in `MainActivity.cs` or `MauiProgram.cs`):\n```csharp\n#if ANDROID\nusing AndroidX.Core.View;\n\n// In your MainActivity's OnCreate, after base call:\nWindowCompat.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(Window, false);\nWindow.SetStatusBarColor(Android.Graphics.Color.Transparent);\nWindow.SetNavigationBarColor(Android.Graphics.Color.Transparent);\n#endif\n```\n\n**Minimal full-screen page example:**\n```xml\n<ContentPage\n    xmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"\n    ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\"\n    Shell.NavBarIsVisible=\"False\"\n    Padding=\"0\">\n\n    <Image Source=\"photo.jpg\" Aspect=\"AspectFill\" />\n</ContentPage>\n```\n\nThe Android piece is the most commonly missed part — without it, the system reserves space for the status/nav bars regardless of your layout settings.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"6e4c6bee-6a57-43e9-9ac4-ea265bb36dd8","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is working on a .NET MAUI app targeting .NET 10 and wants an image to go edge-to-edge (behind status bar and navigation bar). They've set `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` on the ContentPage but still see padding.\n\nIn .NET MAUI, to achieve true edge-to-edge content that goes behind system bars, you need to do more than just handle safe areas. Let me think about what's needed:\n\n1. **Safe area insets** - `IgnoreSafeArea` or setting safe area properties on the page\n2. **Full-screen / immersive mode** - On Android, you need to opt into edge-to-edge display. On iOS, you need to handle the safe area.\n\n\n3. **Platform-specific configuration** - The `SafeAreaEdges` property the user mentioned might not be a standard MAUI property, so I should clarify what the actual MAUI APIs are for controlling safe areas and edge-to-edge rendering. -to-edge in the MainActivity or use window insets APIs. The `NavigationPage` or `Shell` might also be adding its own navigation bar that consumes space. I'm second-guessing whether `SafeAreaEdges` is actually a standard MAUI property—it might be from another framework or a custom implementation. The reliable approaches are `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\"` for iOS and configuring system bar behavior on Android, though .NET 10 might have introduced new APIs I'm not immediately recalling. False\"` on iOS, the Android edge-to-edge setup, and hiding navigation bars from Shell or NavigationPage. I'm not actually sure if `SafeAreaEdges` is a standard MAUI property—it might be from a newer version or a specific library—but the core issue is likely that Shell's chrome or the navigation bar is still adding padding even after attempting to disable safe areas. The most common culprits are Shell's visibility settings, the iOS safe area configuration, and Android's system bar handling not being fully configured together.\n\nI should also check whether the page or its content layout has default padding that's persisting independently of the safe area settings.","outputTokens":1613,"requestId":"D457:2DE6FB:1C1EA28:1FA2582:6A07BF8B"},"id":"f1e165a9-558c-4175-a0d8-f047ffd2db67","timestamp":"2026-05-16T00:51:52.991Z","parentId":"f43e2230-5652-432e-a736-ee72ca809764"}
